ten use the same class names for common elements. Things like header, footer, aside, article, ect. This is how they came up with the HTML5 elements after all. So what are some class names you should avoid using? Here are the ones I would stay away from. Modernizr Related...  <a href="http://themble.com/css-classes-to-avoid-in-your-markup/" title="Read CSS Classes to avoid in your Markup">Read more &#187;</a></p><p>The post <a href="http://themble.com/css-classes-to-avoid-in-your-markup/">CSS Classes to avoid in your Markup</a> appeared first on <a href="http://themble.com">Themble</a>.</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"eddiemachado";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4439:"<p>When marking up your site, you&#8217;ll often use the same class names for common elements. Things like header, footer, aside, article, ect. This is how they came up with the HTML5 elements after all. So what are some class names you should avoid using? Here are the ones I would stay away from.</p>\n<h3>Modernizr Related Classes</h3>\n<p>If you&#8217;re not using <a href="http://www.modernizr.com/">Modernizr</a>, you should be. For a detailed description of what it does, go to the site. The quick answer is, it adds classes to your page so you can adjust for supported features (among other things). So to avoid any issues, you should avoid any classes that contain CSS3 or HTML5 features. For example:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>borderradius</li>\n<li>textshadow</li>\n<li>canvas</li>\n<li>video</li>\n<li>audio</li>\n<li>localstorage</li>\n<li>js</li>\n</ul>\n<p>A few of those can be quite common. I&#8217;ve used classes like <strong>video</strong> and <strong>audio</strong> in the past, mostly without issue. It&#8217;s probably better though, that you use <strong>vid</strong> or <strong>vid-player</strong>. You could use just <strong>player</strong> too, but many js libraries (flowplayer) use that class as well.</p>\n<p>Modernizr also adds classes when there <em>isn&#8217;t</em> support for a certain feature. So you should also avoid the same selectors with &#8220;no-&#8221; in front.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>no-borderradius</li>\n<li>no-textshadow</li>\n<li>no-canvas</li>\n<li>no-video</li>\n<li>no-audio</li>\n<li>no-localstorage</li>\n<li>no-js</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Those will probably only affect older browsers, but really they have enough issues already without adding any more confusion in the mix.</p>\n<h3>WordPress adds classes too</h3>\n<p>WordPress also drops classes into your pages. Things like body classes, post classes, and comment classes can have pretty commonly used names.\n<dl>\n<dt>logged-in / logged-out</dt>\n<dd>It&#8217;s added to the body element so be careful not to use them anywhere else.</dd>\n<dt>archive / single / page / author / search</dt>\n<dd>Dependent on what page you&#8217;re viewing, these classes will be added to the body element.</dd>\n<dt>blog / date / tag / category</dt>\n<dd>Pretty common words here. If you&#8217;re writing markup for WordPress, they are all good classes to avoid.</dd>\n<dt>post</dt>\n<dd>Added as a post class by default. I see this one all the time. If it&#8217;s added automatically, don&#8217;t add it again.</dd>\n<dt>alt / comment / odd / even / parent / children</dt>\n<p>All these are used as comment classes, so stay away.</dd>\n</dl>\n<p>Those are a lot of pretty common words right there. You can see how it would be pretty easy to create a mess. Imagine having a div around your WordPress loop with the class name <em>.post</em>. If you add any styles to it, then not only would that div have them applied, but the post class function would apply the class <em>.post</em> to the actual post <strong>inside the loop</strong>. That&#8217;ll be fun.</p>\n<h3>Microformats</h3>\n<p>Microformats rely on classes to pull data and organize it properly. Adding classes they normally use in situations where they don&#8217;t apply would cause a bit of confusion. Luckily, they aren&#8217;t classes commonly used for anything <em>but</em> Microformats.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>hentry</li>\n<li>vcard</li>\n<li>adr</li>\n<li>fn</li>\n<li>org</li>\n<li>street-address</li>\n<li>locality</li>\n<li>region</li>\n<li>tel</li>\n<li>email</li>\n</ul>\n<p>There&#8217;s a ton more and I&#8217;m sure you&#8217;ve a few of those in markup before. Luckily, the browsers really only read into them if they are inside the <em>vcard</em> class, so it won&#8217;t cause any confusion if you put your <em>.email</em> in the header. It&#8217;s still good to know though.</p>\n<h3>Whatever! I&#8217;ll do what I want!</h3>\n<p>Everyone codes differently, so it&#8217;s entirely up to you what class names you want to use. However, sometimes it&#8217;s easier to simply use the class names that are already available (in the case of WordPress). If the <em>hentry</em> class is already applied to WordPress posts, why add another class to that container? Use the classes your given and be weary of your naming convention. It will make your life easier in the long run.</p>\n<p>The post <a href="http://themble.com/css-classes-to-avoid-in-your-markup/">CSS Classes to avoid in your Markup</a> appeared first on <a href="http://themble.com">Themble</a>.</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"http://themble.com/css-classes-to-avoid-in-your-markup/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_e